Duel to the last blood: MP3 players against mobile phones
We will advise how to choose
While almost every mobile phone can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can call.
It is clear from this that it is better to buy only the phone.
Nevertheless, there are many reasons why you should get an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the way of use and the needs of the future owner.
Perhaps you would hardly buy an expensive high-quality turntable to listen to Maxim Turbulenc's latest album.
First of all, these music products do not come out as LP and from a qualitative point of view there is not even an objective reason.
But if hard-rock, jazz or blues vinyls are crowded on your shelves, you probably dream of such a turntable.
It also works with portable music, i.e. compressed music or simply in MP3 format.
Here, too, there are the categories of price and quality.
For some it may be unacceptable to spend 8,000 crowns on a player, just as a Pink Floyd fan probably hardly digests headphones from twenty crowns on the market.
Two extremes between which there is enough space for everyone.
The choice is wide.
It is up to the battery life.
Some high-quality music players can do much more than just read music, but cell phones don’t even do it by mistake.
There is no other device today that is as universal as a mobile phone.
Alongside the primary functions, calling and texting, it can read music and videos, record both, and has a camera, sometimes better sometimes worse, and maybe it can even browse.
And if we consider smartphones and handsets you will also have a miniature computer in your pocket.
It is a small miracle that no refrigerator can do the grilling and no television can photograph anything.
The universality of the mobile phone also brings disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your phone and the earlier the indicator on the screen will require the charger.
Reading music takes a lot of energy.
Few cell phones can read music for more than twelve hours, usually, and much less.
In this sense, music players (especially the simplest ones) are much more effective.
As for cheap mobile phones, don’t count on them lasting longer than a few hours.
If you still add, from time to time, some calls, get another charger at work for safety, this also applies to the most expensive appliances.
But you won’t have this problem with an MP3 player, even the worst ones last at least 9 hours with continuous functionality with a recharge.
Another problem is when you download music to your phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have the universal USB port and not all of them can be connected to the computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but only a few memory readers are able to do it without an adapter for minicards that are not used in mobile phones.
Readers, with some exceptions (iPods) do not need any special software.
Just fill the device with music via USB from the computer.
Most mobile phones and readers create themselves a media library sorted by performers' names, album name, genre, or by user's classification.
Some devices only reproduce the tree structure of the folders, similar to the Explorer tool in Windows, and some know how to do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobile phones can do more.
When choosing a particular device, be especially interested in the battery strength, memory capacity, quality and type of audio outputs and clearly the ease of use.
If the music you need above all from the background and if you listen to it every day only briefly on the tram you just need a mobile phone that reads MP3.
This can now be done on any mobile phone.
You don’t have to worry too much about what formats your phone or reader recognizes.
The MP3 players support them all, the global majority of the music that comes to you will be in this format.
In addition to this format that belongs to the most common ones, the total majority of devices support music in WMA format.
There is less AAC (the format used by the Apple company and its iPods).
The best mobile phones also allow, for example, to buy music online.
Just visit, through the mobile internet, the corresponding pages of the operator (or another provider) and buy the song or album.
This same service could already be a valid argument for buying a mobile-reader.
Unfortunately, the offer of the operators is miserable and is usually limited only to hits of the moment of the radio.
The prices are not very low.
But it is generally assumed that this mode of selling music (either via GSM, Internet or wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their cell phone behind them.
Anyone who wants to listen to something is in their pocket while the MP3 player is forgotten at home.
However, it also depends on this, if you always wear behind the headphones or at least the wireless headphones.
If not, you can use the built-in player that almost every cell phone, but only a small part of MP3 players, has.
Perhaps the biggest advantage of mobile-readers will be, for many, the price.
The cheapest ones normally cost less than 3,000 crowns.
For 3 and 4 thousand crowns you will already buy a very dignified walkman.
Usually, however, you will be limited by the absence of an entrance for the common headphones.
The best and technically most equipped mobile phones and also with the 3.5 mm socket for the common headphones, cost up to 15,000 crowns.
Instead, the advantage of the readers is, among others, easy handling.
The simplest ones are not necessarily cheaper (see our choice) anyone can really handle them.
The minimum of functions, the similarity of handling once with the common stereo or perhaps the turntable, is obvious.
There is no danger of accidentally hitting the start of the mobile internet network and consequently a giant bill for the transmission of data.
What equipment to take
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable memory cards (type M2, microSD etc.).
Also with regard to the purchase of the respective card, you fall into the 2,000 crowns.
But be careful.
The base models only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2GB.
Only the most expensive ones can do it even with 8 GB memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and want to buy an inexpensive MP3 player, take Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB) you do not have to spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you are one of the most demanding listeners, take the specialized mobile phones - walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have individual keys for MP3 and the convenience of the service so it comes close to the same MP3 player.
In this area, Sony Ericsson has made more progress, which mobile phones of the walkman line have the same scale of use as MP3 players sold separately.
The MP3 players of the above brands provide you with the same service and the same price range up to 4,000 crowns, but with a larger memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (commonly 15 hours, generally up to 35 hours).
The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic as early as this year.
Possibly
Perhaps the mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
There’s something missing here anyway – a virtual operator that forces the traditional ones to lower the price.
Maybe he won't be missing for a long time.
The fact that Czech operators belong to the most expensive in Europe we have already written many times on Mobil.cz.
In the end, <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> also confirmed this, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher in our country than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of the regularization of roaming tariffs perhaps a paradoxical situation will be created - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS will cost less from abroad than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high against Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that would really like to start the fight.
Maybe it sounds absurd, even here we have three mobile networks and coverage highly above 100%.
On the other hand, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this sense, the head of the Czech Telecommunications Council (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>) Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xA1>k, who in the past sometimes expressed that there is no room for another operator in the Czech Republic, also often emphasizes.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with its own network is no longer likely to have many possibilities. (Otherwise, it might be difficult to find other frequencies by now).
But there is another possibility - the virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry of virtual operators into the market that has led to a significant drop in prices, which traditional operators should have reacted to.
At the same time, even before sharks like Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile entered the market, similar voices resonated in Britain as we did.
However, it has been shown that the place for such operators is there and that they can really succeed.
In the end, for example, we do not have to go very far.
In February of this year we informed you about the arrival of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year this operator has managed to gain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta to which in the Czech Republic it belongs, among other things, U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to be able to work effectively, it is enough for them to have far fewer customers than a traditional operator.
They do not bear, that is, relatively high costs for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
Thus, in the world, virtual operators usually present themselves at low cost, offer calls and SMS at low cost, which is often in balance with the offer of the narrowest services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS that cost at least half of its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows can be a pretty good move even betting on a group-target not recently.
This operator focuses, so to speak, specifically on men.
“Real men choose the Mobilking operator they like and can be trusted,” says David Seibertz, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, which produces this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland can also be affirmed by us.
Vodafone press spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a fragmented approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, from the point of view of services it is relatively saturated."
In the Czech Republic no possibility, say mobile network operators
But it seems almost certain that if there will ever be an operator in the Czech Republic it will not be Mobilking.
“There is talk of the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not have many expectations.
The ignition of Mobilking will take place rather in other countries in our area," Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>kov<0xC3><0xA1>, the spokesman of the financial group Penta, said in a telephone dialogue for Mobile.cz.
Thus, it indirectly confirmed that the current operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not very in favour of this idea.
Rather, they try to do everything because you do not create any potential competitors.
For some time now he has not concealed his interest in launching a virtual operator, the GTS Novera group, which would like to take another step to become a real competitor of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nika O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We have a great interest in being able to offer our customers not only fixed services but also mobile telecommunications.
And the sooner it gets better it is.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile network operators.
We have already made progress in negotiations with some of them," said Group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
So maybe better times will come.
The unofficial information shows that the first virtual operator will probably have it by the end of the year.
For now, however, a wall of silence is erected around his creation.
“At the moment we do not believe that there is room in the Czech market for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
So far no subject with a complex and serious project has approached us," Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>en<0xC5><0x88> of the Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2 press section said in his statement to Mobil.cz.
The specificity of the Czech market is also used by other operators.
T-Mobil press spokesperson Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> adds in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: “For now we have not noticed any vital and beneficial commercial project for both of us, on which it is possible to continue to build.”
“On the T-Mobil network, a virtual operator will hardly appear by the end of the year.
At this point, we should have already had a concrete agreement on the table, so that it could be considered on the horizon.”
Vodafone focuses its attention rather on meeting its 3G license requests.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> adds: "We are open to the negotiations of potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost-sharing and infrastructure.
We consider this, from the point of view of customers, the most producer.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common network for fast mobile internet.”
Competent authorities -with complicit operators
The attitude of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to lower prices and thus to a decrease in profits.
Why, then, facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The annoyances around the creation of U:fon testify that when operators hold to one thing they can row on the same side.
Perhaps the great pressure pressed against <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> during the period of creation of U:fon towards the company of T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by the public access information from the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> web pages.
But right now U:fon serves as an argument for which not to accept the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> commented: “The competitive environment of the mobile phone market has recently been enhanced above all with the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
Regarding the type of mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another competitor would place high demands on him and above all on his services.
However, the attitude of mobile operators is surprisingly disinterested by the Czech regulators.
It is not just the attitude of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> that unfortunately in the Czech Republic – unlike Britain and other developed countries – has no competence to interfere in economic competition.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
This, however, has taken its typical position on the whole issue.
"The entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market would be possible after the conclusion of the contract for the rental of the necessary infrastructure between the mobile operator and the virtual operator.
No such contract has been concluded so far because the offer of potential buyers has probably not been interesting enough for traditional operators," said Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa, of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS external relations section, in response to our question.
Such a statement by the representatives of the operators is perhaps not surprising.
Instead, on the part of the office that must defend the interests of consumers and above all take care of the fact that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, it is more than a delicate business.
Especially when Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa adds: "Abroad where virtual operators commonly operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile services."
But, of course, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the lowering of prices are not in <0xC3><0x9A>OHS’s interests.
Truly shocking in the whole situation is the almost emotional harmony of these three operators resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence arises on its own.
Just as the same price of gasoline for all petrol stations is certainly the fruit of coincidence and competitive struggle.
"The section has found no signs of anti-competitive behaviour in this regard and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No operator has a dominant position, so it does not have a corresponding greater responsibility for its behavior in the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile network market to virtual operators may also be missing from the telecommunications regulator," Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, according to which telecommunications are the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, no Czech operator has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer a different approach - for the creation of a virtual operator is always necessary the agreement of the network operator.
And the mobile operator has - logically at the end of the day - the monopoly of its network.
So for a certain portion it must be dominant by force.
But even if we do not admit this argument, for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS it should be a minimum alarming that three mobile operators proceed in such a strangely similar way.
At the same time, complaints from interested parties (including the mentioned company GTS Novera) show that during negotiations with all operators they encounter very similar obstacles.
Downloading responsibility to <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> in telecommunications is a fairly frequent trick with which <0xC3><0x9A>OHS is kept out of the whole thing.
We have already seen this in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it was not possible to promote the expansion of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>'s rights in the field of economic competition in telecommunications until the recent update of the Telecommunications Act, despite the fact that many experts expected the situation to improve.
This fact the representatives of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS need to know more than well, but perhaps their interests are elsewhere.
You can do it when no one is watching
While without noticing it remains the functioning of these pseudo-virtual operators, of which there are even some in the Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that publish their mobile phone service price lists but are only partially public.
These are usually companies that deal with multi-level marketing.
So for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only preset people.
The magic lies in the fact that the company against the operator appears as a classic corporate customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer then receives special price offers (and more).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit a similar pre-sale.
"If the cases you are talking about arise, which we will be interested in, it could be a violation of the terms of the contract, and it could lead to the conclusion of cooperation with this company," Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> replied to the question in question.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity would not reach the ears of those responsible for mobile operators.
Especially in the cases of the 3 companies mentioned it can be thousands of customers.
No operator defends himself at the same time from such an attitude.
From the activity of these companies they make a profit that is not indifferent and at the same time - unlike real virtual operators - they are not harmed in any way with their official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> warns about possible problems: "The law allows for such speculation, but only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They also have to accept that the SIM card in their phone is not registered in their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it like the regular customers of mobile operators.”
But that should be a bit strange at the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>.
In addition, another issue opens up for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such an attitude, why do they block the creation of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has strong enough rights to expose similar activities and if it does not want to, it will not have to be satisfied with the explanation of the operators who have no idea of all this and that their commercial conditions prohibit it.
When we are no longer expensive
As has already been said several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a significant drop in prices for services.
At the same time, in virtually every country where operators were born, traditional operators tried more or less to prevent their creation.
The topics they used were virtually identical - market too small, limit too saturated, problems with the quality of services etc.
But in the developed countries, in these cases, the regulatory bodies have intervened in defense not of mobile operators but of their customers.
Both with formal measures and with non-formal pressure, then came the creation of the first virtual operator and others joined him.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are throwing themselves from one to the other the whole case like a boiling potato.
In our experience, we cannot get rid of the feeling that the lack of clarity of skills in these cases makes him more than comfortable.
But let's not throw away the sponge.
If the behind-the-scenes information is right and the virtual operator will really soon appear from us, the Czech mobile market will get back on track.
If one of the operators had consented to the creation of a virtual mobile operator only <0xC3><0x9A>OHS could hardly remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of the other interested parties.
And maybe we will stop calling at higher prices than the rest of Europe.
