The back door of CBGB, the punk rock monument that closed in 2006, opened on Extra Place, and the road is perhaps best known as the set for the cover photo of the Ramones' album "Rocket to Russia."
“The terrain was beautiful,” said Danny Fields, the Ramones manager, who took the photo in November 1976.
"It was full of garbage, scraps of clothes and pieces of barrels, posters, leaves, ropes."
Some residents, including some bloggers who write about East Village’s “gentrification,” opposed the idea of selling Extra Place, arguing that the piece of public property, modest as it is, should remain public.
Others have praised Extra Place as a rarity – a fragment of almost nothing changed city that should be left alone.
Jeremiah Moss, who has a blog called Jeremiah's Vanishing New York (subtitled, "The Book of Complaints: A Little Nostalgic Look at the Endangered City"), published part of a City History Speech that appeared in The New Yorker in 1952.
The author, Brendan Gill, wrote: "Extra Place is a narrow dead end alley, dark even by day and delimited doors of rusty iron warehouses and windows with sarcasm, with weeks-old newspapers hovering along the lowlands."
With a few exceptions, the road looked almost the same as a recent evening.
A rat was agilely running through the back of the street near a door leading into the CBGB, which is now the site of an aristocratic clothing store.
On the walls there were graffiti and an empty 22-ounce bottle of beer lying next to a group of fresh abandoned newspapers.
Few passers-by said they rarely thought of Extra Place but suggested it would need to be a little embellished.
Mr. Fields, for his part, said he also thinks some people underestimate the attraction of the road in its current state.
"The best years of my life," he said, "were in black, dirty and disgusting places."
The bilingual debate: immersion in English
In this episode of Educational Look, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the position of candidates on bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, senior member in California studies and senior director of educational studies at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is the co-author of the book "Not as Good as You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs to Choose a School."
Truly attracting Hispanic voters is a complicated business.
Barack Obama’s educational projects are a significant example.
Mr. Obama’s campaign notes that, “African-American and Latino students are significantly less likely to graduate than white students,” which is true.
To combat these shortcomings in achieving the goals, Obama’s education plan specifically supports, among other things, “transient bilingual education” for English students.
Yet the question for Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which emphasizes classroom teaching in languages other than English, does not take into account his interest in bridging learning gaps.
Take, for example, Sixth Street Prep, an elementary school in eastern Los Angeles County.
School students are mostly Hispanic and low-income.
More than a third of the students, many of whom have recently arrived, are studying English.
But, among fourth graders, an astonishing 100 percent of students took the upper-level test in the 2008 math status exam.
An equally astonishing 93 percent of fourth graders took the expert-level test on art-of-language-English.
This incredible result was achieved using a different ingredient than Mr. Obama’s preferred.
Sixth Street emphasizes review and exercise, constant assessment of skills, and a “no excuse” attitude.
In addition, and this is where Mr. Obama should take note, according to Linda Mikels, director of Sixth Street, the school’s obstructive approach to English students is “full immersion.”
The use of English emphasizes the almost exclusive use of English in the context of education.
Ms. Mikels, who opposes bilingual education, told me, “We had a fantastic success with a student just coming from Mexico and if you had entered the class 12 months later you wouldn’t have been able to pinpoint which one it was.”
"It works," he observed, "it works for us."
Would Obama model a school like Sixth Street Prep to replicate it in other Spanish-majority schools with English students?
The school’s results make the answer to that question very easy, but the educational policy in its own party (the National Education Associations is a long-time supporter of bilingual education) and its own continued support for bilingual education prevent it from predicting Mr. Obama’s answer.
While he agrees that immigrants should study English, Obama recently made the argument trivial when he said people should stop worrying about “only-English” legislation.
Instead, he said, “you have to make sure your children are able to speak Spanish.”
If Obama really wants to close these achievement gaps, he should carefully consider the educational models that work rather than despise or trivialize them.
