In a city apart, pride and processes of a black life
Hidden in the extensive theme park on the outskirts of Orlando, a few miles from the splendor, the noise, the huge, lies the quiet city where the pride and complications of the African-American experience come to life.
Eatonville, the first all-black city incorporated into the country and the birthplace of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as it was described in 1935: "the city of five lakes, three croquet fields, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, plenty of guava, two schools and no prison."
It is now a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to show their respect to Hurston, the most famous Harlem Renaissance writer.
Yet in many ways, the city he described – and that makes tourists stop by including it in the Florida tour guide produced by the Depression-era Federal Writers’ Project – remains a place apart.
It is as independent, dignified and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted sharing their thoughts with the white man, that “knowing so little of us, he doesn’t know what’s being lost.”
Even now, in a year where a black presidential nominee, Senator Barack Obama, has been called for an opening speech on race, many here remain suspicious of the outsider’s gaze.
“We are very careful about how our story is told,” said Hortense Jones, 59, a lifelong resident and member of the city’s oldest church.
"It must be fair."
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and difficulty.
It is both a historical model of black power-taking and a community of nearly 2,400 where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a literary center but also an example in the shadow of the oaks of the rural culture of the blacks of the south - sometimes disdained, sometimes rewarded - born of American slavery.
Not surprisingly, the residents here are both proud and protective.
And the worry about Eatonville's imagination really started with Zora, who everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced the world to her hometown through sincere, dialect-rich books, such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs of the Florida guide transformed the city, just off Route 17, a road that runs through Florida’s often-forgotten downtown within a backdrop of black history and human drama.
Low as a grancasa in both life and literature, Hurston took readers to the store owned by Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then diverted to more private areas.
"Out of the street to the left," he wrote, "is the modern public school, brown with white finishes, with its well-kept gardens and courtyards, which Howard Miller always looked after, thinking he could barely read and write."
She also mentioned the widow’s new husband Dash and wrote that Lee Glenn “sells drinks of all kinds and whatever fits the passage rooms.”
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston connected Eatonville with self-government but also with illiteracy, second marriage and sex.
Clearly this was not Fodor's.
In fact, it was not a portrait that everyone appreciated.
"Now she was saying it like it was," said Ella Dinkins, 90, one of Johnson's girls who Hurston immortalizes by quoting men who sing coarse songs about their beauty.
He adds, "Some people don't like it."
Hurston is still remembered here as a lively eccentric who frequently returned from her family moved to Jacksonville, Fla.
Augustus Franklin, 77, remembers that when Hurston drove into the city, he used to arrive unannounced in a triumphant Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants in a city that still boasts of decent clothing.
Many residents were fascinated, Mr. Franklin says, while others sighed.
“People were always very happy to see Zora,” Mr. Franklin said.
But, he added, swinging on his chair on the patio at the back above Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "she never stayed long."
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books had gone out of print.
Along with the rest of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in a plateless tomb in Fort Pierce, Fla., where she had lived.
In Eatonville, there were no great commemorative ceremonies, and no great conferences.
"I don't think they understand his contribution to the world or his legacy to everyone," said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows," a Hurston biography published in 2003.
A change took place in the 1980s.
Orange County officials wanted to place a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the two-lane main road.
Orlando’s expansion has already pushed Interstate 4 across the city’s western boundary.
The proposal came when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to its idyllic isolation from the community.
In the 1950s, the battle over racial mixing brought hatred to the community’s doorstep.
“During that time, a group of white boys came and threw oranges and stuff at people sitting on one side,” says Mr. Franklin.
“We actually had a girl who was killed by that one time.
They threw a coconut out of a car."
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston made a request to the Supreme Court for forced integration, calling his decision in Brown against the school office "an insult rather than an honor for my race".
Residents now say that the desegregation of schools, despite being positive in some respects, dilutes Eatonville’s cohesion and jeopardizes the confidence of its young people.
“Black kids were used to being hugged — I remember this — you hugged your teacher in the morning, you hugged your teacher in the evening,” said N. Y. Nathiri, Ella Dinkins’ daughter and the executive director of Preserve the Eatonville Community, a non-profit group.
This lasted, he added, until teachers and students came from the same place.
"You didn't hug your white teacher because your white teacher...- I mean, there's a cultural division there," said Mrs. Nathiri.
Civil rights, however, helped and created space for many more Zora Neale Hurstons - black writer, actress and artist who overcame prejudices, as she did, with cheerful self-confidence and lines such as: "How can some deny themselves the pleasure of my company!
I just can't figure it out."
In 1975, writer Alice Walker began a long journey to Hurston's unmarked grave and began to fight for the resurrection of her reputation.
Five years later, an acclaimed biography of Robert E. Hemenway's Hurston hit the bookshelves, reintroducing it into the American canon.
The highway project arrived just as his most famous daughter had once again turned the spotlight.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The community began designing a festival dedicated to Hurston in 1988 to show what could ruin the state with its highway.
Thousands of fans came to the inaugural event two years later, and every January, many return for the commemoration.
Many years later, the state pulled back from its road project.
"The five lanes of the resurrected highway have brought what would be called high speed, a real pride for the city," said Ms. Nathiri.
Mrs. Boyd puts it simpler: "Now he saved Eatonville."
The victory over the highway project helped change the city’s self-image.
Those from outside the city like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who started coming to church here in 1993, began to appear in large numbers, and residents began to reevaluate the past.
Eatonville joined the public historical register in 1998.
A new one-storey bookstore (called Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on a revamped and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: just six miles from downtown Orlando, it can give the feeling of a side street in the summer rain, as small as when it was founded with just 27 black families in the 1980s.
(It’s 90 percent black today.)
Outsiders who come to search for Eatonville’s story, for its meaning, are often still treated with caution.
A permission asked in advance is required for most of the interviews, to some things — such as murals on the oldest church in Eatonville, painted by a white man, showing black men in the fields — they are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, such as Ms. Jones, a fat teacher, with a weakness for bright red, are still afraid that their island community will be misunderstood.
Yet, as soon as the Hurston festival expanded, a high level of citizen pride also emerged.
Young people, in particular, tend to see Eatonville with Hurston seeing his entire race: beautiful, troubled and all, no better, no worse and proud, creative, great worker, silly and confused like other races and ethnic groups in America.
It is sincere civic affection that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin’s nephew, Edwin Harvey, 18, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the local government or for the Police Department, who said he might need help.
And even those who are younger, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, 11-year-old twins from Winter Park, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
“A lot of people, if they’ve just come in here, they’ll think, ‘Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others,’” Alondra Kenon said after the mess on a recent Sunday.
“But if you really stop and take a moment to look at history, it’s really a pretty city.”
