"I photograph the master away from the scene to extract his character" Günther Bauer, photographer
No heels, no steering wheel, no clothes.
Only the essence of the great masters of flamenco, stripped of the concentration that characterizes the interpretation, to look at the relaxed appearance of the man or woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other hand, the person.
Two inseparable faces, except in private, in those moments away from the public, when the intimacy of a gesture, the depth of a stolen look or the expressiveness of hands, are natural because they do not have to go on stage.
The German Günther Bauer in "Flamenco-People" alternates the theatrical shots of some singers, dancers and guitarists on stage with the lesser known side of these masters.
With this lens, the photographer offers an original iconography of flamenco, capturing it from different visual angles.
The exhibition, included in the programming of the Month of Flamenco Photography, reflects the international importance of this dance, every day more and more," explains the artist and clarifies that in "Flamenco-People" they could also be ordinary people, but seeing the photos, the observer realizes that they are not the typical images of artists, performers or performers on the scene.
These people portrayed "on the street" are "artists capable of transmitting passion, sadness, joy when they are on stage ... and of capturing the audience.
To capture the personality of these great you do not need to portray them on stage,
because their personality and character are internal.
What I was interested in was to create an intimate atmosphere that allowed me to capture with the camera the personality of the greats of flamenco.
With the passion for the festival "Cante de las Minas", Bauer began in 1997 a long journey aimed at portraying singers, guitarists or dancers using a plate camera.
They are portraits that, due to the type of machine and the material, resemble classical photography.
The application of different stylistic techniques breaks with the traditional principles of the image, giving the photo modernity, according to an idea that reflects the conception of the flamenco of Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and is able to surprise every day."
Not dancing, singing or playing in itself, but the personality of the artist, his character, able to conquer the audience with his art.
The search for an encounter with the essential elements, with the magic that becomes visible in a certain way of feeling and being, are and have been the constant of this work, on display these days at the El Fot<0xC3><0xB3>mata gallery.
Famous flamenco artists such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are included in this selection of about seventy portrait artists.
The project has become a sort of flamenco anthology, and will soon be published in a book that will collect the portraits exhibited on the occasion of the exhibition.
The passion for portraiture led Bauer to repeat the idea two years ago with "Portraits of veteran athletes" ("SportARTproject").
Although in "Flamenco-People" the concept is different, the photographer admits "I love to portray people, to know them and to be able to penetrate for a moment in their lives, whether this is a long or short moment.
I think portraiture is the hardest genre in photography.
You meet or compare with people, characters you sometimes don’t even know or who only give you a few minutes to take the photo.
Beyond these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to put my ideas into practice.”
The collection of portraits of contemporary flamenco, entitled "Flamenco-people", is set up at the El Fot<0xC3><0xB3>mata gallery, at number 20 in via de la Mata, parallel to via Alameda de Hercules, and will be open to the public until October 16.
