A Sevillan dancer pays homage to another dancer equally from Seville.
Carmen Valencia Tortola, Catalan father (Florence Tortola Ferrer) and Andalusian mother (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), was born in the district of Triana, and at the age of three moved with the family to London.
She was a free dancer and a specialist in oriental dance.
She led a fascinating life and was a pioneer of female emancipation, the calibre of Isadora Duncan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was a Buddhist and vegetarian, and defended the cause for the abolition of the corset that prevented women from moving freely.
The life of this woman, who marked a revolution in the field of dance and aesthetics in Europe between the two wars, has always fascinated Isabel Bayon.
"I would have loved to work with Pepa Gamboa and she proposed this character to me. It seemed incredible."
She says: “We don’t pretend to tell her whole life, but to collect her spirit.
The titles of his dances suggested some basic elements of flamenco.
So, "the dance of the butterfly" suggested me a guajira, or "the dance of the snake" some tanghi.
Her dance was sensual and I was told that my way of dancing also fits into this aesthetic,” she explains.
The staging includes two exceptional contributions: that of Miguel Poveda, who will sing Isabel again in one of his shows, as a face in "La puerta aperta"; and that of the teacher Matilde Coral, who exceptionally wanted to work with the one who had been his pupil.
"Matilde plays Tortola as an adult, the character of maturity.
I am happy because he has accepted to work in my work and I feel very honored for that.”
The set-up also includes the musical composition and guitarists such as Jesus Torres and Paco Arriaga, the song of Miguel Ortega, the Pulga y Moi of Mor<0xC3><0xB3>n; the percussion of El P<0xC3><0xA1>jaro, as well as the viola of Rafa La Viola and the collaboration of an actor, Juanfran Ju<0xC3><0xA1>rez "who has always played the role of eternal spa accompanist of these artists.
In the work is also present in some form the life of this woman that takes place in distant places, especially for that time, such as India, the United States or Russia, and then all of Europe, since, habitually, he resided in London.
“I wanted to remember her, because I think she’s one of the women who has had an enormous influence in a given historical period and now no one remembers her, let alone considers her work as something of value,” Bayon said.
The show will start today, at 20.30 at the Lope de Vega theater.
