Drivers of relapsed alcoholism will have to install the "alcolock"
The Ministry of the Interior requires drivers with three administrative sanctions for excessive blood alcohol, install in his car the system that prevents driving the vehicle in a state of drunkenness or if he does not blow in the appropriate device.
The measure was announced last June and is already included in the annual report of the State Attorney General, according to which it will be a one-year pilot project.
The purpose of this project is to reintegrate the driver, since he or she will have to attend a rehabilitation course on the road.
In addition to the General Prosecutor’s Office for Road Safety, the Directorate General for Traffic (DGT) and the Fondazione Istituto Tecnologico per la Seguridad dell’Automobile (FITSA) will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of drivers reported more than once to drive in a drunken state then return to driving the car.
The alcoholock would avoid it, because it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the rate of alcohol in the exhaled air and prevents the car from starting if the driver does not blow, or when a higher alcohol concentration is detected than allowed.
The cost is more than 1000 euros and would be at the expense of the sanctioned.
In this regard, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with such devices can reduce up to 65% of infringements committed during the first year of introduction.
And in Spain it is estimated that it could save the lives of 115 people a year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to curb these behaviors before they become criminal offences.
And to facilitate their development, since the legal reform can be carried out on an ordinary basis, and, no doubt, the reform necessary for the criminal procedure would require an organic law.
However, the device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial solution, although it has already been experimentally introduced in some industrial and public vehicles.
Tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on a PSOE initiative in which it proposes to install this system in school buses, as has already been done in France.
