Talking in sleep
Some children talk at night.
I don’t mean those who wake up very agitated to tell us something that happened to them the day before, but those children who talk staying asleep.
The first time it happens, at most you get a scare, but it doesn’t really matter much.
This is a benign alteration of sleep called somniloquium.
It manifests itself with a certain frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Certainly, most of you have been told that you spoke in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (once in life, for example associated with an episode of high fever) or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the baby remembers nothing.
There is no single reason that can explain this phenomenon.
Sometimes they are episodes linked to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, nighttime fears, nighttime enuresis (pissing in bed), or sleepwalking, but not necessarily.
As already mentioned above, it can be associated with very high fever stages, stress or overexcitement situations.
In any case, it is a phenomenon still little studied.
The intensity with which it appears is also extremely variable.
It can happen that the person speaks in a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper or that the opposite happens (crying, screaming, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, it would be advisable to observe the child and possibly consult a specialist to check if there is any issue that is generating an abnormal state of anxiety as an outlet to the situation.
We have said that this is a benign alteration therefore there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (e.g., if coupled with insomnia or stressful situation).
What you can do, however, is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before he goes to sleep.
Proposing quiet games and avoiding programs or TV series that arouse fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children for whom it is tiring to relax, you can use relaxation techniques to help them acquire some inner calm.
This will allow the child to sleep more peacefully.
Once the sleep talks appear try to keep calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will remember nothing of what happened.
Useful advices
Don't wake him.
It is useless, because he is not aware of what is happening, and you would interrupt his sleep.
Although he's talking, he's sleeping and so he's resting.
Remember that if it appears very anxious and the episodes have a certain frequency it is better to consult a doctor or check where such a great anxiety in the child comes from.
If you understand what he is saying (which is not the most common situation), do not fall into the temptation to do him an interrogation to get information.
You will get nothing, because he is asleep and therefore unconscious to organize his thought.
In addition, you are able to hear what he is saying but not to see what he is dreaming to say, so you need to pay close attention to the interpretation of the information and the conclusions that it might lead to.
Never tell your child that you could ask them questions during the night to learn their secrets.
Not even for a joke.
Such a thing causes enormous anguish.
In short, do not worry, it is nothing serious, it is an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
