The meeting - The blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated the tenth anniversary of its foundation yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, as Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, it has regained public confidence, seriously shaken by the blood scandal infected in the years between 1980 and 1990.
As we know, national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected with acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980s.
In the face of such a drama and public protests, the Government of Canada conducted a public inquiry in February 1994, led by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to disseminate recommendations to prevent the resurgence of a similar disaster.
While Judge Krever was delaying a report, some provinces set up a committee with the aim of devising a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the Gélineau et Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Quebec and the Société canadienne du sang (Canadian Blood Society) for all other provinces and two territories.
In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its activities, only 38% of people said they still had confidence in the donation system in Quebec, recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was mortifying.
Thanks to continued efforts to improve the safety of blood collections and field research over the next few years, we have regained public confidence,” she explains, before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the population of Quebec had now confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary, however, is convinced that "trust is something extremely fragile."
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were numerous cases of the human variant of the mad cow in Europe, a new manifestation of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says the one who has been in the presidency since 1998, the year of the foundation.
"And we didn't know at all if that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
One of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports was, therefore, that when there are doubts about a serious disease, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which manifests itself with a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, exclusion measures are taken.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than a month in the UK since 1980 was rejected.
Now, for a few years, it has been shown that without a doubt this disease is transmitted through infected blood.
This episode has thus shown us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle.”
In 1999, a much more efficient technique for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: tests for nucleic acid (TAN) that allow to recognize directly in the blood of donors the presence of the virus and not that of antibodies against it, on which instead the tests used until then were based.
TANs have allowed to reduce the window period, that is, from the moment the person contracted the disease to the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood thanks to our techniques, explains the specialist.
This period could be reduced to less than a week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and therefore not being able to detect them has thus decreased significantly.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS with a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
“In other words, that means that it will be necessary to distribute 12 million blood samples before someone gets infected with the HIV virus.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood samples each year, it will take more than 24 years for a case of HIV transmitted by a transfusion to occur.
I believe that today you can feel at ease in receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health, says the head of the management of Héma-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than a year ago, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the Island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted in the blood by an insect.
You have to be constantly vigilant," continues Dr. Décary before stressing that in addition to having secure resources, Héma-Québec must also provide enough.
“Needs are increasing as the population ages.
As cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need a supply of red blood cells or platelets.
The aging population also has consequences on the number of donors, which on average constitutes only 3% of Quebecers acceptable as donors."
All healthy people who have reached the age of 18 and who meet the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer themselves as donors are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where it is widespread, they will be rejected for a period of one year.
“With this 3% we are able to maintain an inventory capable of meeting the needs of hospitals.
Cases of scarcity are very rare.
But members of this group of donors need to be renewed as they get older and can no longer make donations.
Now it is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to keep them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Nowadays life is so frenetic that it is difficult to find an hour to donate blood,” says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec distributes not only blood samples, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin that is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being deposited at Héma-Québec, which operates the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, there is abundant blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the bank insertion of our thousandth cord blood sample and we plan to take more than a thousand each year.
We should start proposing them for transplants early next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes this practice of cord blood sampling as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed not to have access to it," as Héma-Québec does not have the means to offer this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
