Free Opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Speech
In the September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from M. Patrick J. Garver, vice president and managing director of Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Pursuing an Orwellian logic, the latter claims that the world’s largest gold company has filed a six-million-dollar libel lawsuit against three authors and a small, squatted publishing house with the intention of initiating a “transparent public debate.”
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth they judge, especially in the case of a libel lawsuit, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this substantial difference is completely hidden from Garver.
Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to bring to ruin anyone who dares to stand up for a position contrary to his own.
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the writers and publisher of the book Canada Nero will have to spend a considerable sum of money in order to organize their own defense and fight, with decidedly uneven weapons, against an army of lawyers financed by the practically fundless pockets of the mining company.
Moreover, in these unequal gun battles, the tactic is often to ruin the defendant in order to impose a consensual regulation that obscures the opposition as well as frighten anyone who dares to speak again on the issue.
If Barrick Gold had really wanted a public debate, it was first and foremost public opinion that should have presented its own view of the facts.
Contrary to what happens in many countries where Barrick Gold works, in Canada the debates are usually held with the exchange of opinions and not at the whim of a manganese.
It would therefore have been sufficient for the society to open its books, its documents, and establish a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications and the funding of teams of independent researchers who could shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold doesn’t seem to have too much confidence in public opinion and misrepresents petitions and letters in support of Black Canada’s authors.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can ask for a “public debate” when his contempt for that same audience is obvious?
In the world of the vice president, it seems that this word only refers to the fragrantly paid lawyers and not all Canadians; here is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democratic system, even denigrationists have the right to speak.
What Barrack Gold doesn’t understand – or doesn’t want to understand – is that the public that supports Black Canada’s authors and publishers does so primarily because it rejects the brutal means adopted by the mining company.
This audience is ready to listen to Barrick and judge, but on the basis of civilian exchanges of opinion, and not from the perspective of what many perceive as a kind of slur (seeking the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just given the authors of Canada Nero an ultimatum by urging them to suspend the use of that parola...
Beyond Garver’s surreal speech, the complaint from Barrack Gold constitutes a direct attack on the freedom of university research and the pursuit of truth, indispensable in every democratic society.
It denies the right to citation of authentic sources and to debate on facts and interpretations, which are the very basis of intellectual work.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to study and discuss inconvenient topics for the richest companies in the world, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so by following scientific standards as the authors of Black Canada do.
You have the right to replicate.
For a long time, the university environment, of which we are a part, has been able to handle debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
The excessive measures of Barrick Gold clearly show that, contrary to its claims, it does not seek a transparent debate at all.
