The psychology of bidding in excess: why spend more money?
At auctions, buyers are likely to spend more, to overestimate the goods.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York have been able to uncover the neuro-economic basis for this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, men do not want to stay behind in a race like the eBay auction, so they are available to pay even a higher price.
The research tried to trace the nervous pattern of this “match” at the level of the nervous system through experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lot, the other group of players participated in an auction while using the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method they examined the active areas of the brains of the people participating in the experiment.
In both games participants could win some money, but in the auction game, where the substantial element is to bid more than the other, the striated body under the cerebral cortex comes into play intensively when you lose the game.
This area of the brain, in addition to other functions, plays a role in the "self-gratification" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the price rise is explained by scanning the vehement reaction of the striatum body.
To support their theory, the economists of the research group conducted a financial tracking survey.
In this investigation, three groups tendered against a partner under different conditions.
They reported the actual value of the product in question to the control group and they made their bet.
To another group in addition to this they promised that in case of winning they will receive another prize of 15 dollars.
The third group would have received $15 before the auction, but the group members would have lost the money in the event of a loss at the auction.
The difference between the two groups was that for one of them the win was emphasized, while for the other the loss.
By checking the neurologists' hypothesis, members of the group playing "against loss" were willing to make higher stakes in the control or "winning" group.
“These results are not deducible from any of the previously existing economic theories.
In fact, these so far explained the phenomena that can be found at auctions with the joy of winning and with the avoidance of risk.
Only the methods of creating the neurological image helped to resolve the contradiction between the two theories, so we came to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor at the University of New York's School of Economics.
Hepatitis: when to go to the doctor?
Almost half a billion people in the world suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary chronic liver diseases are among the leading causes of death.
In Hungary the number of patients with hepatitis amounts to one hundred thousand, of which only 7000 are treated: the reason is that many patients do not know that they are infected.
The definition of hepatitis is the collective name for contagious liver diseases caused by several viruses.
There are many similarities between the symptoms, typical are hepatitis and jaundice, but their pathogens and the diseases caused differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E through the food channel (e.g. water and infected foods), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal discharge, saliva).
For travelers it is useful to get vaccinated against viruses A and B, against C there is no vaccine.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating infected foods, accompanied by general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After yellowish spots form on the skin and on the white of the eyes, the stools become light and the urine dark, the healing takes place within two to three weeks.
One million people worldwide die each year from hepatitis B, the most serious variant of the disease, which causes liver cancers and liver cirrhosis.
The main reason is, according to estimates, that only one in ten people receive drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if it is not treated, it can cause liver cirrhosis and liver cancers.
Most infected people do not know they have contracted the disease because pathogens fraudulently destroy liver cells, in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, it is very important to prevent and perform regular medical tests.
This disease is much more common than the average in three groups: those who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts and tattooists.
In the world today, the number of people infected with chronic hepatitis C virus amounts to 200 million.
Since even a routine laboratory examination reveals the disease, it is worth talking to your family doctor when you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
