Who believes in God feels less pain?
According to the results of a recent investigation, religious faith functions as a kind of analgesic that has made the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
Scientists at the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment, examining how faith in God affects the feeling of pain, the British Telegraph reported.
As part of the somewhat bizarre investigation, an electroshock was carried out on 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists, while everyone watched a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to reject much of the pain.
Thanks to the exploratory technique of the human brain, it was discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of the brain responsible for pain control.
The test is the first in a series of research in which scientists, philosophers and theologians from the University take part in addition to academics.
The test was carried out exactly like this: an instrument that emits discharges and passes the electroshock was connected to the left hand of the subject of the experiment.
Researchers asked participants to focus on two paintings, the Virgin Mary painted in the 17th century by Sassoferrato and the Lady with Leonardo da Vinci's hermeline painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the examination hoped that the image of the Virgin Mary originated a kind of religious state among believers, while Leonardo's painting was chosen because it did not differ too much from the other and they considered it to be a calming effect.
The subjects of the experiment spent half an hour in front of the MRI scanner and in this span of time received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive series, while observing either the religious-themed painting or the other.
The Catholics reported that the vision of the Virgin Mary made them feel “safe,” as if “someone was taking care” of them and “they were reassured and pervaded by peace.”
Looking at the religious-themed image they accounted for 12% less pain than when they had Leonardo’s work in front of them.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who took part in the test himself, believes that a similar result can be achieved with any image with a strong effect even for atheists, but it is necessary to find the right image.
"We need to look for an image towards which they nurture very positive feelings, such as a mother or father," the psychologist said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright was pleased with the result of the search.
“The practice of faith should change, and in many cases it manages to change our personality,” Wright added.
After the excellent results, only the question remains whether the painting of a Madonna by Leonardo or another painter of similar caliber is presented to believers, what effect could it have on the control of pain?
Would the vision of a quality Virgin Mary bring better results?
You are what you say about yourself
On the day of Google’s 10th birthday, Google can claim to be in people’s pockets as much as in the sky above their heads; it knows where they’ve spent the holidays, what outpatient clinic they’re attending, and what interests them.
This, however, according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company’s directors, is not yet enough.
What concerns the skeptics who make a comparison with the Orwellian nightmare, they do not see the very substance of the Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google’s main purpose is to collect as much personal data as possible from its users and this is necessary to stick to the original goal of Google’s founders that was: “we put all the information in one system in the world!”.
According to the director of Google interviewed the company, after 10 years of revolutionary work, it is still at the beginning of being able to handle all the information.
Asked what would happen in five years, Schmidt said: “If Google knew how to answer questions like ‘what am I going to do tomorrow?’ or ‘what would be the right job for me?’, the software doesn’t know how to answer seemingly simple questions because it doesn’t know enough about users.”
Not all Internet users are aware that during their Internet searches exactly the words they are looking for are recorded, from which IP address they are searched and on which page the interested parties stop after the search.
By means of the Personalized Search launched two years ago, for example, users can store their browsing history, they can relate to what they have searched and clicked, these then in the long run will generate much better tailored results; on this same logic is based Recommendations with which the system offers us products and services based on our previously declared and registered preferences.
What happens if my data is used against me, if they look at what I do? - users are worried about Google's data monopoly.
In most cases, the reactions of the Internet users are provoked by the fear felt by the size of the potential power represented by the company, and not by the sense of guilt, by the fear of punishment, by the desire for freedom or even by the rebellion against power.
However, one fact is confirmed and that is that all the searched expressions are not only recorded but in justified cases can also be provided to third parties, in such legal cases nothing defends the personal rights of Internet users.
The most striking example of this in recent times has perhaps been the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, in which Google forwarded to the Brazilian government the information that made it possible to identify the pedophiles from the Orkut community page maintained by Google.
Internet users concerned about personal rights sought relief in May when the company - in agreement with the electronic legal protection association EFF - successfully proved the truth in court against the FBI: neither can Google be forced by any point in the constitution to provide any information secretly requested by the FBI.
(At the same time, the federal government has successfully ripped off nearly 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search expressions obtained in reference to the confirmation of the child protection law passed years earlier, but still failed to obtain the search lists of individual users and the entire list of web pages and keywords dating back to two months.)
Google’s judgment is therefore rather contradictory: those who are afraid to provide their personal data scold Google because they believe that this will affect their privacy and privacy by starting to use its services and rise up with the rebellion of multinationals that stand out for the conservative image.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and the proliferation of enthusiasts, activists and computer users appearing in numerous countries see in them the future generation of big companies, the "cool corporation", unlike their rival, Microsoft liquidated as the conqueror of the world because of Windows, although both fight for the same goal.
This can happen because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask its users for an identification code, does not ask for money for its services, the source code is always kept up-to-date and the software package is much more accessible, youthful and cool than the official practice of the software giant.
But it can also happen because geeks see exactly the problematic relationship between personal rights and the internet, which implies one of the most repeated keywords in recent years, the web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is about collaboration, intentionally leaving traces behind us and exploiting the communication channels at our disposal and while the size of these changes for each individual, the substance is the same: show ourselves.
An average young person can create profiles in multiple community pages, from Facebook to Shanghai, can connect them with other services such as Twitter or last.fm that lists their musical tastes, all of these can put them in systems such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, can also write blogs on which automatically appear their latest photo galleries on Piclicka.fm
Meanwhile, we read of numerous exemplary cases from which it is clear that the girl, seeing the series of photos taken in the morning by the common tour of friends, easily comes to know who spent the night with her perfidious boyfriend or a company can fire an employee because he has written a sincere opinion on the corporate summit.
Those who live an online life make sure to show themselves and so we can formulate the fundamental thesis that is hidden behind the behavior of young people.
Those who want to hide something or just want to avoid Google’s monopoly can do so (starting with Scroogle, for example, using Google’s search engine but at the same time voluntarily leaving no traces).
There are not a few people who don’t purposely sign up for community pages to not be found, Google’s online applications, from word processing to image management and news gathering, can be replaced with alternative versions not tied to huge server parks and that don’t make up our best profile yet.
Public opinion is not even waiting in secret for the moment when Google will pull out the claws.
Currently, the company with its $156 billion worth is worth more than IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion) or Coca Cola ($110 billion), AdWords/AdSense advertising spaces also threaten the revenues of advertising agencies, the software services introduced at the time of records do not cause big ones.
However, the critical observers next to all this find alarming points: the corporate summit for example completely rejected the protest of the employees after doubling the line of the corporate nursery, considered too expensive the repeated catering to the daily pleasure of the employees, but all this diminishes the reputation of the Google in front of the fact that in 2006
An internal rule of the company seems to be not to advertise a new service in advance but only when it will be usable, but one thing is certain, that the foreseeable problems of the coming months and years will move the world to a point: while some believe that the project of scanning and storing health books and magazines of Google will take on such proportions that we will soon find ourselves in the face of this American system.
The fact that Google is building a genetic database can offer good material to the next generation of science fiction writers, the Scroogled account of the famous Cory Doctorow describes the future with Orwellian accents, in which a man with Google data can be approached in an alarming way.
