The smart machine mimics the flight of the cormorant
What could be the best method to develop anti-collision technologies if not to imitate the sensors of obstacles found in nature?
For example, the bees.
In the surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the hulls gave the initial strategic impetus to Nissan engineers on how to build the next generation of anti-collision systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the biomimetic robot BR23C, a mini-robot equipped with the properties of bees, with the ultimate goal of creating a system capable of scanning all collisions.
Flying bees form their own oval personal space that really looks a lot like our protective shield - explained Kazuhiro Doi, director of PR technologies and research and development at the exhibition.
Important is the role of the bee's sight, capable of a view of 300 degrees in each direction.
The engineers drew on the telemetric laser idea to copy the function of the bee's view.
The BR23C detects obstacles up to two meters away within a 180-degree radius, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor that immediately turns it into a command to avoid collision.
In a fraction of a second the robot senses the obstacle and then, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes direction by turning the wheels of the measure necessary to avoid the accident.
This avoidance maneuver, unlike the current system, takes place in a completely instinctive way.
“If it weren’t for this, the robot car wouldn’t be able to react quickly to avoid collisions,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robot car project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the damaging and innermost layer of the protective shield, within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must take place at a glance.
But unlike bees the deviation can not go upwards or downwards or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and in the steering direction of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities available to bees to scan other bees, the robot, as a possibility available, can rotate on itself, accelerate and slow down.
The BR23C is powered by lithium polymer batteries, lighter and with high energy density, which means that their lifespan is longer than that of lithium ions.
According to Andoh, the instantaneousness of the intelligent reaction is important, not the processing of the data or even less the ability to store them.
This robot has to process some inputs in a few seconds and react.
There is no need to store and react with intuitive logic based on previous maneuver data, so it only uses a memory of a few dozen Kb.
You do not need a memory of gigabytes or megabytes.
This is the first step towards the development of a technology for the immediate avoidance of collisions that, according to Nissan, will be installed on standard vehicles within 10 years.
Further possibility of application can be represented by the unification with the GPS satellite navigation system that avoiding the obstacles present on the road leads to the destination.
