Listening to high-volume music for an extended period of time using portable music devices such as Mp3 players can cause permanent hearing damage.
This is according to the European Commission, which in a statement published in Brussels cites the opinion of the Scientific Committee on Emerging and Recently Identified Health Risks (Csserri) of the EU, published today.
“From this scientific opinion, it appears that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music with portable musical devices weekly for more than an hour a day holding the device at high volume risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity.”
“I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and high-noise mobile phones may unconsciously damage their hearing in an irreparable way,” says Meglena Kuneva.
"From the scientific findings, a clear risk emerges and we must react quickly.
What matters most, we need to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
We also need to review the existing control systems in the light of this scientific opinion to ensure that they are fully effective and keep up with the new technology."
Brussels had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the high use of portable musical devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to noise from them.
"Scientists confirm that there is cause for concern and the European Commission will now examine together with Member States and stakeholders what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable music devices and related equipment."
At present, there is already a European safety standard limiting the noise level of portable music equipment to 100 dB, but there are growing concerns about hearing damage that can result from excessive exposure to such sources of noise.
You can greatly limit these damages by resorting to solutions such as reducing levels and duration of exposure to noise.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee notes that users of portable music equipment if they listen to music at high volumes (more than 89 decibels) for only 5 hours per week exceed the current limits for maximum noise permitted in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in these conditions for longer periods of time risk a permanent loss of hearing ability after a period of 5 years.
This would affect 5-10% of users of such devices and their number can be quantified between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
