The Elites in Danger
The phenomenon had already manifested a few days ago with the House vote against the $700 billion bailout plan launched by the White House: a significant part of Americans was, and is, more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
The New York Times of yesterday confirms this by informing us that the ongoing crisis is tearing apart the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old East Coast soul, moderate, favorable to federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, instead, conservative, hostile to "those of Washington" and to the world of finance, strong especially in the Central States.
The soul, by the way, which became predominately alive with the vow that I said at the beginning.
But this just mentioned is only one example of the changes, of the great changes, which the ongoing economic earthquake perhaps predicts or already shows: not only in the United States but throughout the West and perhaps not even here alone.
Both in the US and in Europe, the crisis seems to work as an accelerator of incubation phenomena that have long since solidified and finally come to light in the new climate.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the extraordinary revival, of the dual category of state-sovereignty in relation to a kind of re-nationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking and financial institutions that have, yes, close ties with abroad, but that first of all see the budgets of people and families living in a single country, in a single state, very much involved.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those people and families who, among other things, are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically worldwide, but politically it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems to be largely out of the question or has little to say: the clear proof is given by the European Union, which, as usual, divides between different interests and between different state strategies and is unable to decide on any common policy.
And so it is from the government of every single state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and relaunch plans, new rules, and above all the disbursement of funds: since when you get to the bottlenecks it is only the states that have the economic resources, the mass of financial resources that can try to put things back to a standstill.
And they also possess the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of immeasurable value, in certain circumstances, of which probably no market and no international organization will ever be able to dispose to a similar extent.
This new emphasis that the crisis places on the national-state element is, after all, in perfect harmony with the increasing importance that recent developments in the economy tend to attribute to a very closely related factor to that element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had already entered the realm of the network, of increasingly sophisticated technology, of the immaterial, while we were convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we suddenly realized that our future will instead have to deal increasingly with those very little immaterial things.
All things that, look a little bit, can certainly be transported from one place to another of the earth but are still absolutely linked to a circumscribed space, to a territory.
So that those who are sovereign have certainly more cards than those who are not, who have the misfortune of living in a place without crops, without oil and without water.
I come to the second novelty, which, however, presupposes a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritative leadership, the demand of someone who knows how to take control of the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leadership, economic species, turned out to be so inadequate and full of shadow zones.
And together something even deeper and in a certain sense disturbing: a discredit, an insufferability, an image of inadequacy, a sense of remoteness, which tends to involve the entire ruling class in a growing number of Western countries.
That is to say, there seems to be a growing belief in large sections of the population that before their actions are the same ideas of the social elites so far in vogue, their way of feeling and being, their culture in the overall sense of the term, to have made their time and to be increasingly alien to the opinions of the majority.
The demand for leadership, in short, subterraneanly fuels a branched but powerful Bush movement of delegitimization of the ruling classes and traditional political systems, which manifests itself in the sudden "revolts" of the elections or in the sudden turns of the collective moods of these last and most recent times, from the rise of the British to the rise of the conservatives in Austria-Bavaria.
One has the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their formats would say someone, make it increasingly difficult to understand, and therefore to represent, what is not now taking shape in the deep layers of Western societies and that the economic crisis is aggravating.
In the face of all this, talking about a “mass rebellion” on the agenda would be frankly exaggerated.
But keeping your eyes open is certainly not for nothing.
