Goodbye old cinema Paradise, the cities delete the historic rooms
The historic cinemas close in favor of the Multiplex.
“A city without cinema is a blind city, it is like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively photographs what is happening in the major Italian urban centers but also in the cities of the province.
The process of marginalization of the cinemas, with the birth in the periphery of the large multisales and the consequent death by consumption of the monosales in the central areas of the cities, is one of those events that appear to us inescapable and incontrovertible but also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
To disappear are often historical places and loaded with memory, "it is as if a friend, a acquaintance with whom we shared a piece of the road and so many emotions," notes the director of Nuovo cinema Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago earned Tornatore the Academy Award and the Grand Prix of the province of Cannes a way, and that tells the story of a cinematography for the jury of Cannes, and that
The figures provided by Anec, the main trade association, speak clearly: over the past five years, 316 cinemas of the traditional type have closed, and the biggest ones are the halls in the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures is Emilia-Romagna with 82 cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And to demonstrate that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, it is these three Italian regions that have recorded the largest number of new multi-room cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany and in Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian exercise has developed irrationally," notes Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, "it is useful to build new structures but it would be necessary to guarantee the survival of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all its attendees are willing to move into multiplexes.
Not to mention the lack of funding for the fund in favor of businessmen: the previous debt of the state is about 10 million euros.
It is a shame, from an ethical and moral point of view, that the government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector, they would need between 16 and 18 million euros a year.”
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about the closures, decided to run to the shelters with the signing of a protocol between the Municipality and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to protect and promote the cinemas in one room both in the historic center and on the outskirts.
The rules include tax relief measures in favour of operators and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic zone and will have special rates for stopovers and in some car parks.
“It’s an initiative that I like,” notes Giuseppe Tornatore, “and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by setting up other measures.
It is certain, however, that to counter the overpowering of multiplexes, traditional rooms also need to improve the quality of sound and image, because the audience today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to do "New Cinema Paradise", which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass in front of the Rialto or the Quirinale of Via Nazionale now closed, where I have lived so many shared emotions, not to see the posters blackened by dust I turn around the other side.
