When the energy is born from the waves now the big ones come down into the field
It is an exterminated field, which occupies more than 70% of the planet’s surface and is now being discovered by the world’s largest energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources on which they put their eyes, and now they try to put their hands, giants like the Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for a hundred years, and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now the environmentalist instances and the new increase in oil give impetus to the industry.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15 percent of the world’s electricity needs could be covered by offshore waveforms.
That would be twice as much as nuclear power plants currently produce.
And then there would be the currents and the tides.
Colossians on attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a plant in northern Portugal.
When the agreement was announced, it seemed like a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies are betting on marine energy and among these companies have always voted for traditional energy.
“Chevron is studying ocean energy technologies,” said a spokesman for a U.S. oil giant affiliate to the Wall Street Journal, “and is considering the possibility of cooperating with us.”
The cooperation in question concerns obtaining a permit from the U.S. Energy Commission, which is necessary to launch a marine energy exploitation project in Alaska.
This is a signal not recently, especially considering that it is in Alaska that the US continues to extract oil and recently President Bush has launched a plan for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, New York’s Verdant Power Inc. and New Jersey’s Ocean Power are on the path of energy coming from the sea and the amounts invested so far, although not known in detail, indicate an increasing interest, according to observers.
Technology to be developed.
Experts are talking about a technology still in its infancy, also because marine energy does not escape all doubts about the environmental impact.
For now, facilities such as the Portuguese one or some in Scotland are small in size and do not seem to cause major problems to the ecosystem.
However, in order to produce energy on a large scale, technologies with a greater environmental impact must be used.
And the choices are different: the Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys connected to each other.
The wave thrust, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure from pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure drives a turbine which in turn feeds a generator.
Electricity is sent to shore through submarine cables.
For now there are four plants of this type under design, waiting only for federal approval and part of the energy could be used for a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces power for a shopping mall and a parking lot using six underwater turbines in New York’s East River.
The movement of water when there are tides rotates the blades of the turbines, creating a rotary movement that powers a generator.
Verdant said it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to use the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they tell the Institute for Electricity Research, deserves at this time the potential of the tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable than wind, sun or waves and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
It is precisely on the energy of the tides that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others overlooking the coast, have already invested 7 and a half million dollars in 2008 and planned investments up to 35 million for 2009.
